#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:5
msgid "The SGI XFS Filesystem"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:7
msgid ""
"XFS is a high performance journaling filesystem which originated on the SGI "
"IRIX platform.  It is completely multi-threaded, can support large files and "
"large filesystems, extended attributes, variable block sizes, is extent "
"based, and makes extensive use of Btrees (directories, extents, free space) "
"to aid both performance and scalability."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:14
msgid ""
"Refer to the documentation at https://xfs.wiki.kernel.org/ for further "
"details.  This implementation is on-disk compatible with the IRIX version of "
"XFS."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:20
msgid "Mount Options"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:22
msgid "When mounting an XFS filesystem, the following options are accepted."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:24
msgid "allocsize=size"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:25
msgid ""
"Sets the buffered I/O end-of-file preallocation size when doing delayed "
"allocation writeout (default size is 64KiB). Valid values for this option "
"are page size (typically 4KiB) through to 1GiB, inclusive, in power-of-2 "
"increments."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:30
msgid ""
"The default behaviour is for dynamic end-of-file preallocation size, which "
"uses a set of heuristics to optimise the preallocation size based on the "
"current allocation patterns within the file and the access patterns to the "
"file. Specifying a fixed ``allocsize`` value turns off the dynamic behaviour."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:37
msgid "attr2 or noattr2"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:38
msgid ""
"The options enable/disable an \"opportunistic\" improvement to be made in "
"the way inline extended attributes are stored on-disk.  When the new form is "
"used for the first time when ``attr2`` is selected (either when setting or "
"removing extended attributes) the on-disk superblock feature bit field will "
"be updated to reflect this format being in use."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:45
msgid ""
"The default behaviour is determined by the on-disk feature bit indicating "
"that ``attr2`` behaviour is active. If either mount option is set, then that "
"becomes the new default used by the filesystem."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:50
msgid ""
"CRC enabled filesystems always use the ``attr2`` format, and so will reject "
"the ``noattr2`` mount option if it is set."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:53
msgid "discard or nodiscard (default)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:54
msgid ""
"Enable/disable the issuing of commands to let the block device reclaim space "
"freed by the filesystem.  This is useful for SSD devices, thinly provisioned "
"LUNs and virtual machine images, but may have a performance impact."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:59
msgid ""
"Note: It is currently recommended that you use the ``fstrim`` application to "
"``discard`` unused blocks rather than the ``discard`` mount option because "
"the performance impact of this option is quite severe."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:64
msgid "grpid/bsdgroups or nogrpid/sysvgroups (default)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:65
msgid ""
"These options define what group ID a newly created file gets.  When "
"``grpid`` is set, it takes the group ID of the directory in which it is "
"created; otherwise it takes the ``fsgid`` of the current process, unless the "
"directory has the ``setgid`` bit set, in which case it takes the ``gid`` "
"from the parent directory, and also gets the ``setgid`` bit set if it is a "
"directory itself."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:73
msgid "filestreams"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:74
msgid ""
"Make the data allocator use the filestreams allocation mode across the "
"entire filesystem rather than just on directories configured to use it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:78
msgid "ikeep or noikeep (default)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:79
msgid ""
"When ``ikeep`` is specified, XFS does not delete empty inode clusters and "
"keeps them around on disk.  When ``noikeep`` is specified, empty inode "
"clusters are returned to the free space pool."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:84
msgid "inode32 or inode64 (default)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:85
msgid ""
"When ``inode32`` is specified, it indicates that XFS limits inode creation "
"to locations which will not result in inode numbers with more than 32 bits "
"of significance."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:89
msgid ""
"When ``inode64`` is specified, it indicates that XFS is allowed to create "
"inodes at any location in the filesystem, including those which will result "
"in inode numbers occupying more than 32 bits of significance."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:94
msgid ""
"``inode32`` is provided for backwards compatibility with older systems and "
"applications, since 64 bits inode numbers might cause problems for some "
"applications that cannot handle large inode numbers.  If applications are in "
"use which do not handle inode numbers bigger than 32 bits, the ``inode32`` "
"option should be specified."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:101
msgid "largeio or nolargeio (default)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:102
msgid ""
"If ``nolargeio`` is specified, the optimal I/O reported in ``st_blksize`` by "
"**stat(2)** will be as small as possible to allow user applications to avoid "
"inefficient read/modify/write I/O.  This is typically the page size of the "
"machine, as this is the granularity of the page cache."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:108
msgid ""
"If ``largeio`` is specified, a filesystem that was created with a ``swidth`` "
"specified will return the ``swidth`` value (in bytes) in ``st_blksize``. If "
"the filesystem does not have a ``swidth`` specified but does specify an "
"``allocsize`` then ``allocsize`` (in bytes) will be returned instead. "
"Otherwise the behaviour is the same as if ``nolargeio`` was specified."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:115
msgid "logbufs=value"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:116
msgid ""
"Set the number of in-memory log buffers.  Valid numbers range from 2-8 "
"inclusive."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:119
msgid "The default value is 8 buffers."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:121
msgid ""
"If the memory cost of 8 log buffers is too high on small systems, then it "
"may be reduced at some cost to performance on metadata intensive workloads. "
"The ``logbsize`` option below controls the size of each buffer and so is "
"also relevant to this case."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:127
msgid "lifetime (default) or nolifetime"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:128
msgid ""
"Enable data placement based on write life time hints provided by the user. "
"This turns on co-allocation of data of similar life times when statistically "
"favorable to reduce garbage collection cost."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:133
msgid "These options are only available for zoned rt file systems."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:135
msgid "logbsize=value"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:136
msgid ""
"Set the size of each in-memory log buffer.  The size may be specified in "
"bytes, or in kilobytes with a \"k\" suffix. Valid sizes for version 1 and "
"version 2 logs are 16384 (16k) and 32768 (32k).  Valid sizes for version 2 "
"logs also include 65536 (64k), 131072 (128k) and 262144 (256k). The logbsize "
"must be an integer multiple of the log stripe unit configured at **mkfs(8)** "
"time."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:144
msgid ""
"The default value for version 1 logs is 32768, while the default value for "
"version 2 logs is MAX(32768, log_sunit)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:147
msgid "logdev=device and rtdev=device"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:148
msgid ""
"Use an external log (metadata journal) and/or real-time device. An XFS "
"filesystem has up to three parts: a data section, a log section, and a real-"
"time section.  The real-time section is optional, and the log section can be "
"separate from the data section or contained within it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:154
msgid "max_atomic_write=value"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:155
msgid ""
"Set the maximum size of an atomic write.  The size may be specified in "
"bytes, in kilobytes with a \"k\" suffix, in megabytes with a \"m\" suffix, "
"or in gigabytes with a \"g\" suffix.  The size cannot be larger than the "
"maximum write size, larger than the size of any allocation group, or larger "
"than the size of a remapping operation that the log can complete atomically."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:162
msgid ""
"The default value is to set the maximum I/O completion size to allow each "
"CPU to handle one at a time."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:165
msgid "max_open_zones=value"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:166
msgid ""
"Specify the max number of zones to keep open for writing on a zoned rt "
"device. Many open zones aids file data separation but may impact performance "
"on HDDs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:170
msgid ""
"If ``max_open_zones`` is not specified, the value is determined by the "
"capabilities and the size of the zoned rt device."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:173
msgid "noalign"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:174
msgid ""
"Data allocations will not be aligned at stripe unit boundaries. This is only "
"relevant to filesystems created with non-zero data alignment parameters "
"(``sunit``, ``swidth``) by **mkfs(8)**."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:179
msgid "norecovery"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:180
msgid ""
"The filesystem will be mounted without running log recovery. If the "
"filesystem was not cleanly unmounted, it is likely to be inconsistent when "
"mounted in ``norecovery`` mode. Some files or directories may not be "
"accessible because of this. Filesystems mounted ``norecovery`` must be "
"mounted read-only or the mount will fail."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:187
msgid "nouuid"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:188
msgid ""
"Don't check for double mounted file systems using the file system ``uuid``.  "
"This is useful to mount LVM snapshot volumes, and often used in combination "
"with ``norecovery`` for mounting read-only snapshots."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:193
msgid "noquota"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:194
msgid ""
"Forcibly turns off all quota accounting and enforcement within the "
"filesystem."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:197
msgid "uquota/usrquota/uqnoenforce/quota"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:198
msgid ""
"User disk quota accounting enabled, and limits (optionally) enforced.  Refer "
"to **xfs_quota(8)** for further details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:201
msgid "gquota/grpquota/gqnoenforce"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:202
msgid ""
"Group disk quota accounting enabled and limits (optionally) enforced.  Refer "
"to **xfs_quota(8)** for further details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:205
msgid "pquota/prjquota/pqnoenforce"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:206
msgid ""
"Project disk quota accounting enabled and limits (optionally) enforced.  "
"Refer to **xfs_quota(8)** for further details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:209
msgid "sunit=value and swidth=value"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:210
msgid ""
"Used to specify the stripe unit and width for a RAID device or a stripe "
"volume.  \"value\" must be specified in 512-byte block units. These options "
"are only relevant to filesystems that were created with non-zero data "
"alignment parameters."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:215
msgid ""
"The ``sunit`` and ``swidth`` parameters specified must be compatible with "
"the existing filesystem alignment characteristics.  In general, that means "
"the only valid changes to ``sunit`` are increasing it by a power-of-2 "
"multiple. Valid ``swidth`` values are any integer multiple of a valid "
"``sunit`` value."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:221
msgid ""
"Typically the only time these mount options are necessary if after an "
"underlying RAID device has had its geometry modified, such as adding a new "
"disk to a RAID5 lun and reshaping it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:226
msgid "swalloc"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:227
msgid ""
"Data allocations will be rounded up to stripe width boundaries when the "
"current end of file is being extended and the file size is larger than the "
"stripe width size."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:231
msgid "wsync"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:232
msgid ""
"When specified, all filesystem namespace operations are executed "
"synchronously. This ensures that when the namespace operation (create, "
"unlink, etc) completes, the change to the namespace is on stable storage. "
"This is useful in HA setups where failover must not result in clients seeing "
"inconsistent namespace presentation during or after a failover event."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:241
msgid "Deprecation of V4 Format"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:243
msgid ""
"The V4 filesystem format lacks certain features that are supported by the V5 "
"format, such as metadata checksumming, strengthened metadata verification, "
"and the ability to store timestamps past the year 2038. Because of this, the "
"V4 format is deprecated.  All users should upgrade by backing up their "
"files, reformatting, and restoring from the backup."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:249
msgid ""
"Administrators and users can detect a V4 filesystem by running xfs_info "
"against a filesystem mountpoint and checking for a string containing "
"\"crc=\".  If no such string is found, please upgrade xfsprogs to the latest "
"version and try again."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:254
msgid ""
"The deprecation will take place in two parts.  Support for mounting V4 "
"filesystems can now be disabled at kernel build time via Kconfig option. The "
"option will default to yes until September 2025, at which time it will be "
"changed to default to no.  In September 2030, support will be removed from "
"the codebase entirely."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../admin-guide/xfs.rst:260
msgid ""
"Note: Distributors may choose to withdraw V4 format support earlier than the "
"dates listed above."
msgstr ""

